The Presentation: Present your results in 5-10 minutes. To make the presentation using Rmarkdown, do the follows:

- In the left panel, click to Presentation -> Click OK

- Now you have an Rmarkdown that can be knitted to be a html presentation

  • You can also use Rmd samples of the class slides that are available on the class webpage.

  • You do not need to rerun all the codes for the presentation. For example, to show the model comparison, you just need to show the image of the model comparison instead of running all the models again.

  • To inset an image in a slide, use ![](image.png)

III. Predictive Models

Continue with the data from part I. Make sure you do not have any missing values in the data. Use the follows as the target and input variables:

Target Variable: Create the target variable taking value of

  • low if the total charge of a patient (tot) is smaller than the median of the total charge, and

  • high otherwise.

Input Variables:

  • age,sex,raceethn,provider,moa,mod,admtype,campus, los
  1. Use filter function to filter out rows where raceethn=='' or admtype==''. Make sure all the categorical variables are factor, numeric variables are numeric. Set Training : Testing Split = 10 : 90
library(caret)
library(mlbench)
library(rlang)
library(lubridate)
library(rpart)
df <- read_csv('midterm.csv')
df <- df %>% filter(raceethn!='',admtype!='')
df$tot2 <- ifelse(df$tot<median(df$tot),'low','high')
df <- df %>% mutate(target=as.factor(tot2),
                    age=as.numeric(age),
                    sex=as.factor(sex),
                    raceethn=as.factor(raceethn),
                    provider=as.factor(provider),
                    moa=as.factor(moa),
                    mod=as.factor(mod),
                    admtype=as.factor(admtype),
                    campus=as.factor(campus),
                    los=as.numeric(los))
df <- df %>% select(target,age,sex,raceethn,provider,moa,mod,admtype,campus, los)

set.seed(2020)
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(df$target, p = .10, 
                                  list = FALSE)
df_train <- df[ splitIndex,]
df_test <- df[-splitIndex,]
  1. Train a decision tree using rpart. Plot the decision tree. Plot the variable importance ranked by the tree.
model1 <- rpart(target ~ ., data = df_train,
                 control = rpart.control(maxdepth = 3))
library(rattle)
fancyRpartPlot(model1)

barplot(model1$variable.importance)

  1. Using caret for this question. Set Training Control to be: Use Cross-Validation of 5 folds across all models. Train & tune at least 2 different models (i.e.two different values for method= in the train function of caret). Plot the hyper-parameter tuning plots for each model.
trControl = trainControl(method = "cv",
                         number = 5)
tuneGrid = expand.grid(mtry = 2:4,
                       splitrule = c('gini', 'extratrees'),
                       min.node.size = c(1:10))
forest_ranger <- train(target~., data=df_train, 
                    method = "ranger", 
                    trControl = trControl,
                    tuneGrid = tuneGrid)
plot(forest_ranger)

tuneGrid = expand.grid(mfinal = 10,
                       maxdepth = c(1:10))
Adabag <- train(target~., data=df_train, 
                    method = "AdaBag", 
                    trControl = trControl,
                    tuneGrid = tuneGrid)
plot(Adabag)

  1. Plot the comparison of the models in 3.
results <- resamples(list('Random Forest' = forest_ranger,
                          'Ada Bag'= Adabag))
bwplot(results)

  1. What is your final selection for the model? Test the accuracy of your final model on the test data.
pred <- predict(Adabag, df_test)
cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = df_test$target)
cm$overall[1]
##  Accuracy 
## 0.8339853
  1. Create another target variable (binary), decide the input variables and redo 1 to 5.
df1 <- read_csv('midterm.csv')
df1 <- df %>% filter(raceethn!='',admtype!='')
df1$los2 <- ifelse(df1$los<median(df1$los),'Short','Long')
df1 <- df1 %>% mutate(target = as.factor(los2),
                    age = as.numeric(age),
                    sex = as.factor(sex),
                    raceethn = as.factor(raceethn),
                    provider = as.factor(provider),
                    moa = as.factor(moa),
                    admtype = as.factor(admtype),
                    campus = as.factor(campus))

df1 <- df1 %>% select(target,age,sex,raceethn,provider,moa,admtype,campus)

                                  list = FALSE)

                 control = rpart.control(maxdepth = 3))

trControl = trainControl(method = "cv",
                         number = 5)

                       splitrule = c('gini', 'extratrees'),
                       min.node.size = c(1:10))
forest_ranger1 <- train(target~., data=df_train1, 
                    method = "ranger", 
                    trControl = trControl,
                    tuneGrid = tuneGrid)

                       maxdepth = c(1:10))
Adabag1 <- train(target~., data=df_train1,

  1. Write a paragraph to summarize the section and give your comments on the results.

This section was about using the data to predict a target variable such as total payment or length of stay. We used certain input variables and not others when making models to predict the target variable. The models I made were a decision tree, a random forest, and an Ada bag. For predicting total payment, the Ada bag model had a higher training accuracy than the random forest, but for predicting length of stay, the random forest model had a higher training accuracy. The testing accuracy for the Ada bag model when predicting total payment was .834. The testing accuracy for the random forest when predicting length of stay was .66, not very good.
